  <div class="pb-12 mt-5">
    <div class="text-xl py-1">Hey there ðŸ‘‹</div>
    <div class="text-5xl font-bold">I'm Keyvan Majd</div>
    <div class="text-3xl py-3 font-bold">CS PhD Student @ ASU</div>
    <div class="col-12 text-justify">
      <br />
      <p class="text-lg text-justify">
        I am currently a PhD student in the <a
          href="https://scai.engineering.asu.edu"
          >School of Computing and Augmented Intelligence</a
        > at <a href="https://asu.edu">Arizona State University</a>, co-advised
        by <a href="http://henibenamor.weebly.com">Dr. Heni Ben Amor</a> and <a
          href="http://fainekos.net">Dr. Georgios Fainekos</a
        >. I graduated my M.Sc. in Electrical Engineering from <a
          href="https://www.ncat.edu">North Carolina A&T State University</a
        > in 2019. Before that, I received my B.Sc. in Electrical Engineering from
        <a href="https://en.um.ac.ir">Ferdowsi University of Mashhad</a> in 2015.
      </p>
      <br />
      <p class="text-lg text-justify">
        My research primarily focuses on enhancing the capability of robots to
        operate safely in real-world environments, especially in scenarios
        involving human interaction. I have explored different safety-critical
        domains, including assistive robotics, autonomous navigation, and
        mobility. I approach this by combining the strengths of planning and
        control with data-driven techniques. Specifically, my research topic
        includes integrating the global optimization techniques with robot
        learning to ensure the robot follows a set of safety specifications. To
        achieve this, I am developing a novel framework combining imitation
        learning and neural network repair to learn safe policies for robots. I
        am also interested in developing computationally efficient
        optimization-based techniques for learning safe control policies in
        robot learning.
      </p>
    </div>
